      "x": "AFFINITY. Affinity is how strongly a drug binds its receptor, measured by the dissociation constant KD — the concentration that occupies 50% of receptors at equilibrium. The relationship is inverse: higher affinity means lower KD, because a tightly-binding drug needs only a low concentration to fill half its receptors. Low affinity means you need a higher concentration to achieve the same occupancy. And the headline caution, which Parmar repeated: strong binding does not equal high efficacy. Affinity gets the drug onto the receptor; intrinsic activity (efficacy) decides what happens next."
