      "x": "AMPICILLIN and AMOXICILLIN. These two are the aminopenicillins. Ampicillin is the drug of choice for Listeria (an exam-reliable pairing) and is acid-stable but not penicillinase-resistant. Amoxicillin is the oral workhorse — better absorption, less diarrhea than ampicillin, and the standard endocarditis prophylaxis before dental work in at-risk patients. Their shared weakness is exactly the ReClaude setup: plasmid-mediated penicillinases from organisms like E. coli and H. influenzae hydrolyze them."
