      "x": "CHLOROQUINE AND ITS RESISTANCE BACKUPS. Chloroquine is the first-line blood schizonticide; it inhibits plasmodial heme polymerase, so toxic free heme piles up inside the parasite. At proper doses it is safe. The problem is resistance — worldwide. When the strain is chloroquine-resistant, you have a short menu of backups: oral quinine (often with doxycycline), mefloquine (which damages parasite membranes; CDC limits its use to curb resistance), atovaquone-proguanil (Malarone), and the artemisinin combination artemether-lumefantrine (Coartem). Knowing that resistance forces the switch — and knowing the names you switch to — is the high-yield distinction."
